  "local_port": 46288,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Who are some great but lesser known female Indian freedom fighters?",
  "response": "India's struggle for independence was marked by the invaluable contributions of numerous women who played pivotal roles, often overshadowed by their male counterparts. Here are some great but lesser-known female Indian freedom fighters who made significant impacts in the fight against British colonial rule:\n\n1. **Kittur Rani Chennamma (1778\u20131829)**\n   - **Region:** Kittur, Karnataka\n   - **Contributions:** One of the earliest female freedom fighters, Rani Chennamma led an armed rebellion against the British East India Company in 1824 after the annexation of her kingdom under the Doctrine of Lapse. Her valor and resistance inspired future generations of freedom fighters.\n\n2. **Rani Gaidinliu (1915\u20131993)**\n   - **Region:** Nagaland\n   - **Contributions:** A Naga spiritual and political leader, she led the fight against British colonialism and the influence of Christianity in her region. Imprisoned for 14 years, she was awarded the Padma Shri in 1956 for her contributions.\n\n3. **Sukanya Valavalkar**\n   - **Region:** Maharashtra\n   - **Contributions:** A prominent figure in the Salt Satyagraha, she participated in the Dandi March and faced arrest for her involvement. Her efforts were crucial in mobilizing women in the coastal regions to join the independence movement.\n\n4. **Durgawati Devi (1904\u20131942)**\n   - **Region:** Uttar Pradesh\n   - **Contributions:** Known as \"Durga Bhabhi,\" she was a fearless revolutionary who played a key role in the Kakori Train Robbery of 1925, aimed at funding the revolutionary activities against the British.\n\n5. **Vijaya Lakshmi Pandit (1900\u20131990)**\n   - **Region:** Uttar Pradesh\n   - **Contributions:** Sister of India's first Prime Minister, Jawaharlal Nehru, she was an active participant in the independence movement, organizing women\u2019s participation in protests and advocating for civil rights.\n\n6. **Begum Hazrat Mahal (1820\u20131879)**\n   - **Region:** Awadh (modern-day Uttar Pradesh)\n   - **Contributions:** After the Indian Rebellion of 1857, she took command of the forces in Lucknow and fought valiantly against the British, showcasing remarkable leadership and resilience.\n\n7. **Aruna Asaf Ali (1909\u20131996)**\n   - **Region:** Bengal (now West Bengal)\n   - **Contributions:** A prominent figure in the Quit India Movement of 1942, she hoisted the Indian National Congress flag at the Gowalia Tank Maidan during a significant protest, becoming an iconic symbol of resistance.\n\n8. **Matangini Hazra (1912\u20131942)**\n   - **Region:** West Bengal\n   - **Contributions:** A fearless leader, she participated in numerous protests against British rule. Remarkably, she was assassinated while leading a procession in support of independence, demonstrating her unwavering commitment.\n\n9. **Usha Mehta (1917\u20132017)**\n   - **Region:** Gujarat\n   - **Contributions:** Known as the \"Night Watchman of the Congress,\" she played a crucial role in maintaining communication among freedom fighters through radio during the Quit India Movement. Her efforts were instrumental in coordinating underground activities against the British.\n\n10. **Kamala Devi Chattopadhyay (1890\u20131938)**\n    - **Region:** Bengal\n    - **Contributions:** A social reformer and activist, she worked tirelessly for women's rights and education while participating in the freedom movement. Her advocacy helped empower countless women to join the struggle for independence.\n\nThese women exemplify courage, resilience, and unwavering dedication to India's freedom. Their stories, though less highlighted, are integral to the rich tapestry of India's independence narrative.",
